1. Iterate through the string character by character.
2. For each character, check if it is an opening bracket. If it is, push it into the stack.
3. For each character, check if it is a closing bracket. If it is, check if the top of the stack has the matching opening bracket. If it doesn't, return false.
4. If the stack is empty after iterating through the string, it means all opening brackets have been matched, so return true.

This solution uses a stack data structure to keep track of the brackets encountered so far. The time complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the string, as we iterate through the string once. The space complexity is also O(n), as we use a stack with a size of n. The energy implications are low, as the solution only involves simple operations and does not consume significant energy.

